AGI - An unexploded bullet > in an envelope delivered in the office, then a series of miners' letters. A national manager of the Fiom Cgil> denounces it, which immediately receives great solidarity, while the Committee for Order and Public Safety assigns it first an escort agent and then a strengthened surveillance, with a service car and two agents following it in all its movements. He also writes a media campaign to not make the unionist feel alone, Rosita Galdiero, 46 years of Benevento.
Threats date back to 2022, but intimidation was false, according to the Prosecutor of the Republic of Benevento, who transmitted the acts to the colleagues of Rome, for territorial competence. The Gip in Rome set the preliminary hearing for 2 July next. Rosita Galdiero is accused in competition with his driver, > employee of the Fiom Cgil, of having staged the various episodes of threats, as well as of detention of the unexploded bullet that on 9 June 2022 was found in&nbsp; an envelope affissated in the dock of the offices Fiom of Rome.
Other letters were sent to Solopaca, in the province of Benevento, others delivered at the same time to the trade unionist in his home of Rome and in the offices of the Fiom of Rome and Benevento. According to the investigators of the Digos of Benevento, who started the investigation, to 'confection' materially the threats would have been the driver, Fulvio Piccirilli>. In fact, the investigators began to investigate in 2021, when the first suspicious episodes began. In fact, the unionist's mother was approached by some people she knew and reported her miner messages to her daughter. Then a minatory message was delivered to the mailbox of the house of Solopaca and later, another placed under the door of the Roman dwelling. But it was the bullet that put Digos agents on the right track to rebuild everything. The bullet delivered to intimidate the unionist was in fact the property of his driver, who held arms. Some environmental interceptions then allowed to understand that Galdiero and Piccirilli were packing the envelope that would contain the bullet and that was delivered to the Fiom headquarters of Corso Trieste in Rome.&nbsp;
Galdiero and Piccirilli are charged with illegal port and detention of an unexploded bullet, crime simulation and scam.
